Enter the command that is on the following line to test the Karatsuba algorithm. This test case multiplies a 13500-digit integer
with itself, and so the multiplication is likely large enough (the maximum of the number of digits of the two numbers being multiplied)
for the Karatsuba algorithm to calculate the result faster than the traditional algorithm. This is because Karatsuba is asymptotically
faster than the traditional algorithm, so Karatsuba is not usually faster for smaller multiplications, but for larger multiplications after
some threshold, Karatsuba will become faster than the traditional algorithm. Note that the following command will take some time to complete running
(around 30-60 minutes), depending on the hardware of your device. Plugging in your device and maximizing its performance settings while this command
is running is highly recommended to speed up the multiplication.

./karatsuba
